{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 16:29:17.000070", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\\n\\nOverview\\n- Topology: 2-leaf, 2-spine, 1 super-spine EBGP Clos fabric. Hosts: pc_0_0 on leaf_router_0_0 (10.0.0.0/24) and pc_0_1 on leaf_router_0_1 (10.0.1.0/24).\\n- Control-plane: EBGP across leaves/spines/super-spine is established and exchanging expected /24 prefixes.\\n- Data-plane: pc_0_1 is reachable across the fabric; pc_0_0 is not reachable at L3 despite L2 adjacency being healthy.\\n\\nKey Findings\\n\\n1) Control-plane health (EBGP)\\n- All BGP sessions are established and stable:\\n  - leaf_router_0_0 (AS 65200) peers with both spines and shows 4 neighbors, PfxRcd=7; routes include 10.0.1.0/24 via 172.16.0.56.\\n  - leaf_router_0_1 (AS 65201) peers with both spines and shows 4 neighbors, PfxRcd=7; routes include 10.0.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.58.\\n  - spine_router_0_0 and spine_router_0_1 show 6 neighbors each (super-spine + leaves), learning and advertising expected /24s.\\n  - super_spine_router_0 shows 8 neighbors; route table contains all 10.0.x.0/24 and 10.1.x.0/24 prefixes with appropriate next-hops.\\n- FRR routing tables on all routers include:\\n  - 10.0.0.0/24 via leaf_router_0_0\\n  - 10.0.1.0/24 via leaf_router_0_1\\n  - All /31 interconnects present as connected.\\nConclusion: The fabric’s control-plane is normal; prefixes are properly learned and propagated.\\n\\n2) Data-plane reachability\\n- Cross-host:\\n  - Many hosts can ping 10.0.1.2 (pc_0_1) successfully (0% loss, low RTT). This shows the fabric is forwarding traffic correctly to/from leaf_router_0_1 and to that host.\\n  - pc_0_0 ↔ pc_0_1 fails from the perspective of pc_0_0 (timeouts), and leaf_router_0_0 cannot ping 10.0.0.2 (pc_0_0).\\n- L2 adjacency on pc_0_0’s access link is healthy:\\n  - ARP resolution works both ways:\\n    - leaf_router_0_0: arping to 10.0.0.2 returns replies from f6:1e:09:51:7d:dd.\\n    - pc_0_0: arping to 10.0.0.1 returns replies from 3e:4d:0d:24:74:f4.\\n  - Neighbor tables show entries:\\n    - leaf_router_0_0: “10.0.0.2 lladdr f6:1e:09:51:7d:dd … DELAY/REACHABLE”\\n    - pc_0_0: “10.0.0.1 lladdr 3e:4d:0d:24:74:f4 STALE”\\n  - Interface state/counters:\\n    - pc_0_0 eth0 and leaf_router_0_0 eth4 are UP/LOWER_UP with small but non-zero RX/TX.\\nConclusion: Physical link and L2 (ARP) are fine between pc_0_0 and leaf_router_0_0.\\n\\n3) Host pc_0_0 IP behavior\\n- pc_0_0 cannot ping its default gateway (10.0.0.1) or even 127.0.0.1:\\n  - ping 10.0.0.1: 100% loss.\\n  - ping 127.0.0.1: 100% loss.\\n- iptables on pc_0_0 shows a drop rule in OUTPUT:\\n  - “-A OUTPUT -m length --length 10:65535 -j DROP”\\n  - Counters confirm it is active: Chain OUTPUT shows packets/bytes dropped (e.g., 40/3336).\\n- Given INPUT policy ACCEPT and no INPUT drop rules, echo-requests arriving from the router would be received. However, echo-replies sourced by pc_0_0 are dropped by the OUTPUT rule (and even locally generated pings to 127.0.0.1 are blocked), explaining:\\n  - leaf_router_0_0 → pc_0_0 ICMP failure (host never sends replies).\\n  - pc_0_0 → anywhere ICMP failure (host never transmits IP packets).\\nConclusion: pc_0_0 is blocking all outbound IP packets due to an iptables OUTPUT chain length-based DROP that matches essentially all normal packets.\\n\\nLocalization of Fault\\n- Faulty device: pc_0_0.\\n- Evidence:\\n  - L2 adjacency and ARP success between pc_0_0 and its leaf proves link and MAC-level communication work.\\n  - BGP and routing in the fabric are healthy; routes to 10.0.0.0/24 exist everywhere.\\n  - pc_0_0 cannot even ping loopback (127.0.0.1), which isolates the problem to local host IP output filtering.\\n  - iptables rule present on pc_0_0 actively drops outbound IP traffic: -A OUTPUT -m length --length 10:65535 -j DROP.\\n\\nRoot Cause\\n- Misconfigured firewall (iptables) on pc_0_0 that drops all outbound IP packets with length >= 10 bytes. This prevents pc_0_0 from responding to any IP traffic (including ICMP echo-replies), rendering 10.0.0.2 unreachable at L3 despite a healthy fabric and L2 connectivity.\\n\\nImpact Assessment\\n- Only traffic to/from host pc_0_0 (10.0.0.2) is affected at L3.\\n- The 10.0.0.0/24 network remains advertised by leaf_router_0_0 and present in the fabric’s RIB/FIB; however, the endpoint 10.0.0.2 is effectively black-holed because it cannot source any IP packets.\\n- Other hosts and prefixes (e.g., 10.0.1.2) operate normally across the fabric., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='2502ca25-3322-44fb-95e2-1a87f4ac96b1'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
